<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-calculus-of-vector-valued-functions">
	<title>Domains, Ranges, Graphs, and Level Curves</title>

	<subsection>
		<title>Domain and Range</title>

		<definition>
			<title>Domain and Range</title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					The <term>domain</term> of a function is the set of all inputs for that function, and the <term>range</term> is the set of all possible outputs. More formally, if a function <m>f</m> takes inputs from a set <m>X</m> and outputs elements in a set <m>Y</m>, then the domain of <m>f</m> is the set <m>X</m>, and the range is the set of all <m>y \in Y</m> for which <m>y = f(x)</m> for some <m>x \in X</m>, which we might write in set notation as <m>\{ y \in Y: y = f(x)\ \text{for some}\ x \in X \}</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</definition>

		<p>
			In calculus, we often define the domain of a function <m>f</m> <em>implicitly</em>, by defining <m>f</m> in terms of an expression, and then letting the domain of <m>f</m> be the set of all values which, when substituted into that expression, lead to a well-defined quantity. For instance, we might discuss <sq>the function</sq> <m>f(x,y) = x/y</m>, by which we mean the function with domain <m>\{ (x,y) \in \R^2 : y \neq 0 \}</m> and range <m>\mathbf{r}</m>.
		</p>

		<p>
			For a scalar-valued function <m>f(x,y)</m> of two-variables, the domain of <m>f</m> is a subset of <m>\R^2</m>, and we may can therefore sketch the domain.
		</p>

		<activity>
			<introduction>
				<p>
					Sketch the domains of the following functions:
				</p>
			</introduction>

			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						<m>
							f(x,y) = \ln(y - x^2) + \sqrt{x}
						</m>.
					</p>
				</statement>

				<solution>
					<p>
						The expression that defines the function <m>f</m> consists of the sum of two terms, and so to find the domain of <m>f</m>, we must identify where both terms are well defined.
					</p>

					<p>
						The term <m>\ln(y - x^2)</m> is well defined when the input to <m>\ln</m> is positive, i.e. when <m>y - x^2 > 0</m>. We may rearrange this inequality to read <m>y > x^2</m>
					</p>

					<p>
						The term <m>\sqrt{x}</m> is well-defined when the input to <m>\sqrt{\cdot}</m> is non-negative, i.e. when <m>x \geq 0</m>.
					</p>

					<p>
						So <m>f</m> is well-defined when both <m>y > x^2</m> and when <m>x \geq 0</m>, and so the domain of <m>f</m> is the set of all points <m>(x,y)</m> such that <m>x \geq 0</m> and <m>y > x^2</m>. Using set notation, we can also write the domain as the set
						<me>
							\{ (x,y) \in \R^2: x \geq 0\ \text{and}\ y > x^2 \}
						</me>.
						The set is the region in the plane bounded from below by the parabola <m>y = x^2</m>, and on the left by the <m>y</m>-axis, as depicted in <xref ref="fig-8-3-domain-of-ln-sqrt"/>.
					</p>

					<figure xml:id="fig-8-3-domain-of-ln-sqrt">
						<caption>Domain of <m>f(x,y) = \ln(y - x^2) + \sqrt{x}</m></caption>
						<image source="melissa-fig-1.png" width="45%"/>
					</figure>
				</solution>
			</task>

			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						<m>f(x,y) = e^x \sin y</m>
					</p>
				</statement>

				<solution>
					<p>
						The expression defining the function <m>f</m> consists of the product of <m>e^x</m> and <m>\sin y</m>, and so <m>f</m> is well-defined precisely when <m>e^x</m> and <m>\sin y</m> are both well-defined. Both expressions are well-defined for all inputs. And so the domain of <m>f</m> is the set <m>\R^2</m>.
					</p>
				</solution>
			</task>

			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						<m>f(x,y) = \frac{\sqrt{x}}{\sqrt{y}}</m>
					</p>
				</statement>

				<solution>
					<p>
						The expression defining <m>f</m> is a fraction with numerator <m>\sqrt{x}</m> and denominator <m>\sqrt{y}</m>. The expression is therefore well-defined when both the numerator and denominator are well defined, <em>and</em> when the denominator is non-zero.
					</p>
					<p>
						The numerator <m>\sqrt{x}</m> is well-defined when <m>x \geq 0</m>. The denominator <m>\sqrt{y}</m> is well-defined when <m>y \geq 0</m>, and is non-zero when <m>y > 0</m>.
					</p>
					<p>
						So the domain of <m>f</m> is the set of all <m>(x,y) \in \R^2</m> with <m>x \geq 0</m> and <m>y > 0</m>, or in set notation, the set
						<me>
							\{(x,y) \in \mathbb{R}^2 : x \geq 0\ \text{ and }\ y > 0\}
						</me>.
						This set is the first quadrant in the <m>xy</m>-plane, including the positive <m>y</m>-axis, but excluding the origin and the positive <m>x</m>-axis. See <xref ref="fig-8-3-domain-of-sqrt-frac-exercse"/>.
					</p>

					<figure xml:id="fig-8-3-domain-of-sqrt-frac-exercse">
						<caption>Domain of <m>f(x,y) = \frac{\sqrt{x}}{\sqrt{y}}</m></caption>
						<image source="melissa-fig-2.png" width="80%"/>
					</figure>
				</solution>
			</task>
		</activity>

	</subsection>

	<subsection>
		<title>Graphs and Level Curves</title>

		<definition>
			<title>The Graph of a Function</title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					The <term>graph</term> of a function <m>f</m> is the set of all pairs <m>(x,f(x))</m>, with <m>x</m> in the domain of <m>f</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</definition>

		<p>
			When <m>f</m> is a scalar-function of two variables, the graph of <m>f</m> is a set of triples <m>(x,y,f(x,y))</m>, and thus a subset of <m>\R^3</m>, and can therefore be visualized as a surface. See <xref ref="fig-8-3-figure-example"/> for a picture of the graph of the function <m>f(x,y) = x e^{-x^2-y^2}</m>.
		</p>

		<figure xml:id="fig-8-3-figure-example">
			<caption>A graph of the function <m>f(x,y) = x e^{-x^2-y^2}</m>.</caption>

			<image width="80%" xml:id="img-8-3-figure-example">
				<shortdescription>
					A graph of a function of two variables.
				</shortdescription>
				<description>
					<p>
						A graph of the function <m>f(x,y) = x e^{-x^2-y^2}</m>
					</p>
				</description>
				<asymptote width="100%">
					import graph3;
					size(200,200,IgnoreAspect);

					real f(pair z) {return z.x*exp(-z.x*z.x-z.y*z.y);}

					draw(surface(f,(-2,-2),(2,2),nx=30,Spline),red+opacity(0.8));

					xaxis3(XZ()*"$x$",Bounds,InTicks(Label,2,2));
					yaxis3(YZ()*"$y$",Bounds,InTicks(beginlabel=false,Label,2,2));
					zaxis3(XZ()*"$z$",Bounds,InTicks);
				</asymptote>
			</image>
		</figure>

		<definition>
			<title>Level Curves and Contour Plots</title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					A <term>level curve</term> of a scalar function <m>f</m> of two variables is the curve consisting of pairs <m>(x,y)</m> satisfying the equation <m>f(x,y) = c</m>, for some <m>c \in \R</m>. A <term>contour plot</term> is a sketch in <m>\R^2</m> depicting level curves of a function <m>f</m> for many different values of <m>c</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</definition>

		<p>
			The different values of <m>c</m> which are chosen to be depicted in a contour plot are often obtained by varying <m>c</m> by a common difference, obtaining <sq>consecutive</sq> level sets.
		</p>

		<activity>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Sketch a contour plot for the function
					<me>
						f(x,y) = e^{x^2 + y^2}
					</me>
					by sketching the level curves <m>f(x,y) = c</m> with <m>c = 1</m>, <m>c = e</m>, <m>c = e^4</m>, and <m>c = e^9</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>

			<solution>
				<figure>
					<caption>Level curves of <m>f(x,y) = e^{x^2+y^2}</m></caption>
					<image source="melissa-fig-3.png" width="100%"/>
				</figure>
			</solution>
		</activity>

	</subsection>
</section>